Side walls with window. If you aren't wiring your shed for electricity, then windows are your only source of light. Try to face your windows east and west to maximize the amount of sunlight that can enter your shed. Also keep in mind that windows effectively prevent you from using that portion of the wall as hanging storage space, so avoid putting windows in every available spot. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f9/Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet4-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet4-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f9/Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet4-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet4-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Roof rafters. A sloped roof will help prevent any water damage, and keep debris from resting on top of the roof. Rafters can be utilized for storage as well. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet5-Version-2.jpg/v4-460px-Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet5-Version-2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet5-Version-2.jpg/v4-760px-Build-a-Storage-Shed-Step-3Bullet5-Version-2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
